  "chunk_index": 38,
  "summary": "During an interrogation, Emma (impersonating Julia) admits to Inspector Corrado that she and Patrick lied about returning from Milchester together; she actually took an earlier bus at four o'clock and went for a walk through the fields. The questioning is interrupted by a telephone call from Mrs. Harmon, who reports that Miss Marple has gone missing from the parsonage and has not returned. Mrs. Harmon expresses fear and mentions a cryptic note Miss Marple left behind.\n\nAt the Blacklock estate, Letitia Blacklock becomes distressed, and her pearl necklace breaks, scattering beads across the floor. While Phyllida suggests the pearls might be a gift from Randall Goodale, Cordeaux questions if the pearls are genuine, noting that if they were real, they would be worth a fortune.\n\nInspector Corrado travels to the parsonage, where he meets Mrs. Harmon and Julian. They examine Miss Marple's note, which contains a series of disjointed phrases: \"Lamp. Violet. Where is the bottle of aspirin? Death of the Delicious. Consultation. Bravely bear the torture of pain. Iodine, pearl. Letti. Berni. Pension.\" Corrado suspects these words may relate to Letitia Blacklock's pearls. As he prepares to search for Miss Marple, Constable Fletcher calls out to him from a laurel tree.\n\nMeanwhile, a tense dinner at the estate concludes in silence. Patrick feels he has lost favor, and Letitia appears exhausted and fearful. Emma maintains an air of indifference, expressing her desire to pack and leave, noting that she expects an arrest warrant to arrive at any moment.",
